{{Refimprove|date=February 2017}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Esophageal motility disorder | synonyms = Esophageal dysmotility (ED) | image = | caption = | symptoms = | complications = | #nset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} An '''esophageal motility disorder''' ('''EMD''') is any [[medicine|medical]] disorder causing difficulty in [[swallowing]], [[regurgitation (digestion)|regurgitation]] of food and a [[spasm]]-type pain which can be brought on by an allergic reaction to certain foods. The most prominent one is [[dysphagia]]. It is a part of [[CREST syndrome]], referring to the five main features: [[calcinosis]], [[Raynaud phenomenon|Raynaud syndrome]], esophageal dysmotility, [[sclerodactyly]] and [[telangiectasia]].<ref>Winterbauer RH (1964). "Multiple telangiectasia, Raynaud's phenomenon, sclerodactyly, and subcutaneous calcinosis: a syndrome mimicking hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia". Bulletin of the Johns Hopkins Hospital 114: 361–83. {{PMID|14171636}}.</ref>
==Symptoms== There are contractions along the lower esophagus when this condition happens. These contractions prevent the passage of food.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uwmedicine.org/health-library/Pages/esophageal-motility-disorders.aspx|title=Esophageal Motility Disorders - UW Medicine|first=UW|last=Medicine|website=www.uwmedicine.org}}</ref> ==Diagnosis== ===Types===
[[Dysphagia]] could be for solid only or for solid and liquid. * Solid dysphagia is due to obstruction such as [[esophageal cancer]], [[esophageal web]], or [[Stenosis|stricture]]. * Solid plus liquid dysphagia is due to esophageal motility disorder (or dysmotility) either in the upper esophagus ([[Myasthenia Gravis|myasthenia gravis]], [[stroke]], or [[dermatomyositis]]) or lower esophagus ([[systemic sclerosis]], CREST syndrome, or [[achalasia]]). ==Treatment== {{Empty section|date=September 2017}}
