{{Orphan|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = Hereditary cerebral hemorrhage with amyloidosis | image = Crystal structure of human cystatin C monomer.png | alt = | caption = Cystatin C(or Cystatin 3) which is involved in this condition | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}} '''Hereditary cystatin C amyloid angiopathy''' ('''HCCAA''') is a rare, fatal [[amyloid]] disease in young people in [[Iceland]] caused by a mutation in [[cystatin C]]. Most of the families with the defect [[gene]] can be traced to a region in the northwest of [[Iceland]], around [[Breiðafjörður]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16612982 | volume=16 | issue=1 | title=Hereditary cystatin C amyloid angiopathy: genetic, clinical, and pathological aspects. | date=Jan 2006 | journal=Brain Pathol | pages=55–9 | doi=10.1111/j.1750-3639.2006.tb00561.x}}</ref>
[[Mutation]]s in the cystatin 3 [[gene]] are responsible for the [[Iceland]]ic type of hereditary [[cerebral amyloid angiopathy]], a condition predisposing to [[intracerebral haemorrhage]], stroke and [[dementia]].<ref name="pmid2541223">{{cite journal |vauthors=Levy E, Lopez-Otin C, Ghiso J, Geltner D, Frangione B |title=Stroke in Icelandic patients with hereditary amyloid angiopathy is related to a mutation in the cystatin C gene, an inhibitor of cysteine proteases |journal=J. Exp. Med. |volume=169 |issue=5 |pages=1771–8 |date=May 1989 |pmid=2541223 |doi= 10.1084/jem.169.5.1771 |pmc=2189307}}</ref><ref name="pmid16612983">{{cite journal |last=Levy |first=E |last2=Jaskolski |first2=M |last3=Grubb |first3=A |title=The role of cystatin C in cerebral amyloid angiopathy and stroke: cell biology and animal models |journal=Brain Pathol. |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=60–70 |date=January 2006 |pmid=16612983 |doi= 10.1111/j.1750-3639.2006.tb00562.x|url=}}</ref> The condition is inherited in a [[Dominance relationship|dominant fashion]].
