The '''Seychelles Child Development Study''' is a project created in 1986 by the Ministries of Health and Education in [[Seychelles]], in cooperation with the [[University of Rochester]] and the [[University of Ulster]]. Its goal is to monitor the effects of mercury exposure (primarily [[mercury in fish|low-level exposure from fish consumption]]) on infants and young children, especially with regard to [[neurodevelopmental disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.urmc.rochester.edu/pediatrics/research/Seychelles-Child-Development-Study.aspx | title=Seychelles Child Development Study | publisher=[[University of Rochester]] | accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> In the study, hair mercury levels are used as the index of exposure.<ref name=WASP>{{Cite journal | last1 = Myers | first1 = G. J. | last2 = Davidson | first2 = P. W. | last3 = Cox | first3 = C. | last4 = Shamlaye | first4 = C. F. | last5 = Choisy | first5 = O. | last6 = Cernichiari | first6 = E. | last7 = Choi | first7 = A. | last8 = Sloane-Reeves | first8 = J. | last9 = Axtell | first9 = C. | last10 = Gao | first10 = P. | last11 = Clarkson | first11 = T. W. | title = The seychelles child development study: Results and new directions through twenty-nine months | doi = 10.1007/BF02409644 | journal = Water, Air, & Soil Pollution | volume = 97 | pages = 53–61 | year = 1997 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> A number of scientific studies have been produced as a result of this project, which have generally concluded that there is no evidence that [[methylmercury]] consumption results in an increased risk of neurodevelopmental disorders,<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Myers | first1 = G. J. | last2 = Davidson | first2 = P. W. | last3 = Cox | first3 = C. | last4 = Shamlaye | first4 = C. F. | last5 = Palumbo | first5 = D. | last6 = Cernichiari | first6 = E. | last7 = Sloane-Reeves | first7 = J. | last8 = Wilding | first8 = G. E. | last9 = Kost | first9 = J. | last10 = Huang | first10 = L. S. | last11 = Clarkson | first11 = T