[[File:TELUGU GANGA ^ATMAKUR,AP - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Telugu Ganga canal in Atmakur, Andhra Pradesh]] [[File:Poondi Reservoir with water capacity.jpg|thumb|Poondi reservoir]] The '''Telugu Ganga project''' is a water supply scheme implemented by [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]] to provide drinking water to [[Chennai]] city in [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is also known as the Krishna Water Supply Project, since the source of the water is the [[Krishna river]] in [[Andhra pradesh]]. Water is drawn from the [[Srisailam Dam|Srisailam reservoir]] and diverted towards Chennai through a series of inter-linked canals, over a distance of about {{convert|406|km|mi}}, before it reaches the destination at the Poondi reservoir near Chennai. The main checkpoints en route include the [[Somasila]] reservoir in [[Pennar]] valley, the Kandaleru reservoir, the 'Zero Point' near [[Uthukkottai]] where the water enters Tamil Nadu territory and finally, the [[Poondi reservoir]], also known as Satyamurthy Sagar. From Poondi, water is distributed through a system of link-canals to other storage reservoirs located at [[Red Hills Lake|Red Hills]], [[Sholavaram Lake|Sholavaram]] and [[Chembarambakkam]].
The project was approved in 1977 after an agreement was reached between Tamil Nadu and the riparian states of Krishna river: Andhra Pradesh, [[Maharashtra]] and [[Karnataka]]. According to the agreement, each of the three riparian states were to contribute {{convert|5|e9cuft|e6m3}} of water annually, for a total supply of {{convert|15|e9cuft|e6m3}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Shiva | first = Vandana | title = Ecology and the Politics of Survival: Conflicts Over Natural Resources in India | year = 1991 | publisher = Sage Publications, New Delhi | url = http://www.unu.edu/unupress/unupbooks/80a03e/80A03E0h.htm | accessdate = 2007-09-17}}</ref> This number was revised down to {{convert|12|e9cuft|e6m3}} in 1983 after accounting seepage and evaporation loses.
The water initially supplied by the canal was disappointing, delivering less than {{convert|500|e6cuft|e6m3}}. In 2002, the religious leader [[Sathya Sai Baba]] announced a scheme of restoration and lining of the canal; a private undertaking. With an extensive rebuilding of the canal and several reservoirs, the project was completed in 2004, when Poondi reservoir received Krishna water for the first time.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hindu.com/2004/03/09/stories/2004030913280300.htm | date = 2004-03-08 | accessdate = 2007-09-17 | title = Kandaleru water reaches Satyamurthi Sagar | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu}}</ref> The supply of water to Chennai city in 2006 was {{convert|3.7|e9cuft|e6m3}}.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060807/nation.htm#3 | date = 2006-08-06 | accessdate = 2007-09-17 | publisher = The Tribune | title = AP to release Krishna waters to Chennai}}</ref> After the re-lining and reconstruction, the Kandaleru-Poondi part of the canal was renamed Sai Ganga.<ref>The Hindu: Chennai benefits from Sai Baba's initiative by Our Special Correspondent, December 1, 2004, [http://www.hindu.com/2004/12/01/stories/2004120113280300.htm Available online]</ref><ref>The Hindu: Project Water by Hiramalini Seshadri, June 25, 2003, [http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2003/06/25/stories/2003062500110300.htm Available online]</ref><ref>The Hindu: Water projects: CM all praise for Satya Sai Trust, February 13, 2004 [http://www.hindu.com/2004/02/13/stories/2004021301330500.htm , Available online]</ref>
==Jerdon's Courser== The area has however continued to be threatened by illegal construction work and activity related to a project proposed to link the rivers of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatogether.org/2006/mar/env-courser.htm |title=Illegal construction threatens Courser |year=2006|author=Kohli, Kanchi|publisher=Civil Society Information Exchange Pvt. Ltd.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Jeganathan, P.|author2=Rahmani, A.R.|author3=Green, R.E.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2005 |title= Construction of Telugu-Ganga Canal in and around two protected areas in Cuddapah District, Andhra Pradesh, India. Immediate threat to the world population of the critically endangered Jerdon’s Courser ''Rhinoptilus bitorquatus''. Survey Report. |publisher=Bombay Natural History Society, Mumbai, India.|url= https://archive.org/details/CanalAndTheCourser}}</ref>
